name: 04-Model-Training-And-Evaluation
content:
Model Training and Validation:


Overview:

The project uses a combination of unsupervised anomaly detection and explainable AI techniques to identify fraudulent transactions.

  • Model Selection:
  • Isolation Forest is used as the primary anomaly detection model to separate fraudulent (isolated) transactions from normal ones.
  • The model is well-suited for high-dimensional financial datasets and is effective at spotting rare, unusual behaviors.
  • Training Process:
  • Input features include gaps, ratios, frequency counts, and control metrics derived during the data preparation phase.
  • The model learns patterns of “normal” transactions and isolates deviations that indicate potential fraud.
  • No explicit fraud labels are required; anomalies are identified based on statistical separation.
  • Validation Approach:
  • Threshold-based validation: Transactions with isolated_prediction < 6 are flagged as anomalies.
  • Back-testing on historical data: The model is validated against known suspicious/fraud cases to check recall.
  • Cross-feature SHAP validation: SHAP values are used to explain model outputs and ensure the identified anomalies align with business logic (e.g., duplicate invoices, inflated hours, collusion patterns).
  • Explainability & Interpretability:
  • SHAP Summary highlights whether features (e.g., billed quantities, hours, bank account links) increased or decreased fraud risk.
  • SHAP Feature Importance ranks features by their overall contribution to anomaly detection.
  • This ensures model outputs are transparent and trusted by audit and compliance teams.
  • Continuous Monitoring:
  • Predictions and RCA are stored in SQL tables for review and editing.
  • Feedback loops from investigators and finance teams help refine thresholds and improve accuracy over time
